title: Formal Performance Review Meeting
structured_data: {"explanation": "If no improvement is observed, a formal meeting is scheduled in a neutral setting. The discussion recalls previous exchanges, states the lack of improvement, and clarifies expectations. Any managerial gaps in resources or information must be corrected promptly. The meeting concludes with clear expectations and timelines."}

title: Restriction on New Cost Engagement
structured_data: {"explanation": "When tooling or production means are unpaid, no new material orders or cost engagements are allowed. The customer must be informed professionally that production cannot proceed without payment, making further cost engagement prohibited."}

title: Formal Review with HR or Witness
structured_data: {"explanation": "When issues persist, communication must be formally documented with HR or a witness present. The discussion reviews prior steps, facts, support provided, expectations, deadlines, and consequences. A formal letter is prepared in advance, delivered during the meeting, and signed for record-keeping."}

title: Internal Responsibility Check Before Escalation
structured_data: {"explanation": "Before restricting production or charging recovery costs, the company must verify that delays are not caused internally, such as late documentation, pricing issues, non-conforming parts, or premature invoicing."}

title: Accuracy and Discipline in Invoicing
structured_data: {"explanation": "Invoices must be accurate and complete, including correct quantities, prices, delivery status, and recipient. Invoicing mistakes or overshipments increase the risk of payment delays and disputes."}

title: Ownership and Accountability
structured_data: {"explanation": "Individuals are expected to fully own their responsibilities and take all necessary actions to ensure success. Accountability includes learning from mistakes and improving performance rather than avoiding responsibility."}

title: Trust
structured_data: {"explanation": "Trust enables autonomy and ownership and must be built through clear objectives, communication, delegation, and feedback. Managers and teams share responsibility for maintaining trust."}

title: Group Values and Ways of Working
structured_data: {"explanation": "This subject defines the core values and behavioral principles guiding how the group operates globally. It emphasizes agility, ownership, trust, teamwork, compliance, and customer focus to support growth and performance with limited resources."}

title: Identification of Customer Payment Delays
structured_data: {"explanation": "Customer payment delays must be identified early, especially for tooling or production means already engaged. Any request for parts requiring new material orders or significant costs must trigger a payment status check."}

title: Late Payment Prevention and Invoicing Discipline
structured_data: {"explanation": "This subject defines preventive measures to reduce the risk of late customer payments. It focuses on clear payment terms, disciplined and accurate invoicing, proactive reminders, and transparency toward customers regarding consequences of late payment. The objective is to secure cash flow and avoid disputes through anticipation rather than escalation."}

title: Commercial and Financial Risk Management
structured_data: {"explanation": "This domain defines the rules and controls used to manage commercial exposure, customer payment risks, and financial commitments. It aims to protect the company from unnecessary costs while maintaining professional customer relationships."}

title: Cooperation and Teamwork
structured_data: {"explanation": "Effective collaboration across functions and regions is essential. Knowledge sharing and avoiding isolated solutions improve efficiency and results."}

title: Allocation of Recovery Costs to the Customer
structured_data: {"explanation": "If customer payment delays cause production postponement and endanger the project, any additional costs required to recover the delay must be charged to the customer. These costs are only applicable when the delay is not caused internally."}

title: Compliance with Laws and Standards
structured_data: {"explanation": "Compliance with laws and standards is mandatory to protect the company and individuals and ensure sustainable operations."}

title: Respect
structured_data: {"explanation": "Respect governs all internal and external interactions. Disrespect undermines performance and trust, while constructive communication and support enable success. Persistent lack of respect or engagement is incompatible with remaining in the organization."}

title: Company Culture and Leadership Principles
structured_data: {"explanation": "This domain defines the cultural foundations and leadership behaviors required to operate successfully in a complex, global, and resource-constrained environment. It sets expectations for collaboration, responsibility, decision-making, and customer interaction across all locations."}

title: Determination
structured_data: {"explanation": "Determination encourages persistence, initiative, and resilience. Effort and commitment are valued even when outcomes are uncertain."}

title: Rule on Cost Engagement in Case of Customer Payment Delay
structured_data: {"explanation": "This rule defines how to act when a customer is late in paying for tooling or production means while requesting parts that require additional costs. It prevents engaging new expenses without secured payment and clarifies cost responsibility when delays jeopardize projects. The objective is to protect the company financially while maintaining transparent and professional customer communication."}

title: Early Detection of Underperformance and Non-Cooperative Behavior
structured_data: {"explanation": "Managers are expected to identify early warning signs such as missed deadlines, poor quality work, lack of responsiveness, disengagement, excessive talking, or recurring association with failures and gossip. Early detection enables rapid corrective action and prevents escalation."}

title: Communication of Late Payment Consequences
structured_data: {"explanation": "Customers must be informed in advance of the consequences of late payment, such as reminders, delivery stops, or interest charges. Transparency supports enforceability and payment discipline."}

title: People Management and HR Governance
structured_data: {"explanation": "This domain defines the rules, guidelines, and processes governing people management, performance, discipline, and managerial responsibilities. It ensures fair treatment, legal compliance, and consistent management practices across the organization."}

title: Customer Satisfaction and Crisis Behavior
structured_data: {"explanation": "Customers must be treated professionally with solution-oriented behavior, especially during crises, to maintain trust and performance."}

title: Priority of Group, Plant, Department, Individual Interests
structured_data: {"explanation": "Decisions prioritize customer satisfaction, then group, plant, department, and individual interests to ensure alignment and long-term success."}

title: Proactive Payment Reminder Process
structured_data: {"explanation": "An automatic reminder should be sent to the customer approximately one week before the payment due date. Proactive reminders reduce unintentional delays and improve on-time payment."}

title: Informal One-to-One Discussion
structured_data: {"explanation": "The first step is an open and informal discussion to share concerns and listen to the employees perspective. The manager expresses expectations, offers support, and clearly states the hope for rapid improvement. This step aims to resolve issues without formal escalation."}

title: Disciplinary and Performance Management Guideline
structured_data: {"explanation": "This guideline defines a structured and progressive approach to address underperformance or non-cooperative behavior. It prioritizes early correction, transparency, documentation, and managerial responsibility. The process follows clear escalation steps, involving HR when required, with termination as a last resort. The objective is to give individuals a fair opportunity to correct behavior while protecting the company legally and operationally."}

title: Definition of Payment Terms and Invoicing Triggers
structured_data: {"explanation": "Payment terms and invoicing triggers must be clearly agreed with the customer, including what event authorizes invoicing such as shipping or delivery. Clear agreements reduce disputes and payment delays."}

title: Second Formal Review and Termination Decision
structured_data: {"explanation": "If behavior does not improve, a second formal meeting reiterates expectations, sets a final deadline, and clearly states the risk of role change or termination. If no corrective action follows, termination is executed as the conclusion of the process, supported by documented evidence."}
